The death toll from Covid-19 has hit 1,604 after 11 more patients succumbed to the virus on Tuesday. The Health ministry announced that 404 more people tested positive for the virus from a sample size of 4,878 tested in 24 hours. This represents a positivity rate of 8.2 per cent. The new cases comprised 364 Kenyans with the other 40 being foreign nationals; 266 were men and 138 women aged between eight months and 79 years. “There are 871 patients admitted in various health facilities countrywide with 6,284 on home based-isolation and care. Forty-six patients are in the intensive care unit, 23 of whom are on ventilator support and 17 on supplemental oxygen,” Health CS Mutahi Kagwe said in a statement. The CS further noted that six more patients are under observation. “Another 46 patients are separately on supplemental oxygen out of whom 35 are in the general wards while 11 are in the high dependency unit,” he added. Some 527 patients recovered from the disease on Tuesday, raising the number of recoveries to 73,979. From the number, 408 were from the home-based care while 119 were discharged from various hospitals across the country. Nairobi recorded 118 cases followed by Kilifi with 110, Mombasa with 66, Makueni with 26, Nakuru with 23, Kiambu with 12, Kisumu with 11 and Turkana with nine cases. Kwale and Nyeri had five cases each, Siaya and Kajiado had four cases each, Murang’a three, Machakos two while Meru, Kakamega, Kericho, Kirinyaga, Marsabit and Lamu each recorded one case. At subcounty level, 21 of the cases in Nairobi came from Lang’ata, 17 from Westlands, 13 from Dagoretti North, 10 from Kamukunji, nine from Kibra, eight from Ruaraka, six from Embakasi West and five from Roysambu. Embakasi East, Embakasi South, Kasarani and Mathare recorded four cases each with Dagoretti South, Makadara and Starehe having two while Embakasi Central and Embakasi North had one case each. Edited by Henry Makori